      SEC v. crypto exchanges
   =20
 =20

The US Securities and Exchange Commission began cracking down on crypto in =
2017. At the time, there was a vogue for what were called ICOs, initial coi=
n offerings, in which some crypto company or project=C2=A0would raise money=
 by selling crypto tokens to public investors. The ICO promoters =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0the people behind the crypto project =E2=80=94=C2=A0would put out a w=
hite paper describing their project and promising brilliant innovations and=
 huge profits, and they would=C2=A0sell a bunch of tokens for money. There =
would generally be very little in the way of disclosure or investor rights.=
 For promoters, the ICO was attractive because it was a way to raise a lot =
of money from enthusiastic and gullible retail investors without following =
securities laws. Many, many, many ICOs turned out to be complete vaporware,=
 either frauds or functionally indistinguishable from frauds.
For the SEC, the ICO was obviously illegal: These tokens were obviously sec=
urities, and the ICOs were obviously unregistered securities offerings. (Al=
so, many of them were frauds.)=C2=A0And so the SEC started bringing enforce=
ment actions against ICO promoters, basically making them give the money ba=
ck and promise not to do it again, and the ICO boom quickly fizzled.
The SEC, I think, learned three lessons from this experience:
=09Almost all crypto tokens are securities.=09Winning (or settling) cases a=
gainst crypto projects for doing illegal securities offerings is pretty eas=
y.=09Especially when they are also frauds.

The crypto industry also learned some lessons from this experience. The =E2=
=80=9CICO,=E2=80=9D as an initialism, went away, but crypto projects kept s=
elling tokens to raise money. But a new set of best practices emerged that =
more or less conceded the SEC=E2=80=99s point that selling tokens to raise =
money to build a project is a securities offering. Startup crypto projects =
largely stopped selling tokens to public retail investors in the US: They m=
ight sell to retail investors in more crypto-friendly jurisdictions, but in=
 the US they would only sell to accredited institutional investors, crypto =
hedge funds and venture capitalists. (Under US securities laws, private off=
erings to institutional investors are exempt from registration requirements=
.) The venture capitalists would sign a lockup, agreeing not to sell their =
tokens for some period of time. (Under US securities laws, selling securiti=
es to a venture capitalist who immediately turns around to dump them on the=
 public is treated as a public securities offering, but if the VC holds the=
 securities for at least a year, she can sell them freely.
  [1]
)
The project might=C2=A0do what is called a SAFT, a =E2=80=9Csimple agreemen=
t for future tokens,=E2=80=9D in which the VC pays the crypto project now a=
nd gets back a contract promising delivery of the project=E2=80=99s tokens =
in, say, a year. The theory here is that the SAFT fundraising is a securiti=
es offering =E2=80=94=C2=A0the crypto project is selling investment contrac=
ts for cash =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the underlying=C2=A0tokens=C2=A0are not secu=
rities; the=C2=A0tokens are just a form of currency for use in the crypto p=
roject. They are, in crypto lingo, =E2=80=9Cutility tokens=E2=80=9D; people=
 buy them not as speculative investments in a business but to=C2=A0use=C2=
=A0them to do crypto-y stuff.
I have sometimes explained ICOs by saying that =E2=80=9Cthey=E2=80=99re lik=
e if the Wright Brothers sold air miles to finance inventing the airplane.=
=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Raising financing from investors to build a speculative new =
technology=C2=A0feels like a securities offering, so ICOs are securities of=
ferings, but=C2=A0actually existing airline miles=C2=A0are not securities: =
They are a loyalty program, a way to pay for an airline seat. The SAFT conc=
ept is a way to embody this difference: Selling the tokens before the proje=
ct exists is a securities=C2=A0offering, but once the project is running an=
d the tokens are useful, the tokens are just tokens, not securities. And so=
 the SAFT might say that the VC pays now to get tokens in the future, and t=
he SAFT actually delivers the tokens when the project is up and running and=
 the tokens are useful.
  [2]

The SAFT is not the only way to do it, though; even if the tokens are alway=
s securities, selling them in private placements to VCs and locking the VCs=
 up for a year is more or less a way to comply with securities laws. Broadl=
y speaking, the US securities laws regulate mostly=C2=A0public=C2=A0sales o=
f securities, widespread sales to retail investors; private placements to b=
ig investors are less regulated.
In any case there are plenty of crypto projects, these days, that the SEC h=
as=C2=A0not=C2=A0gone after for doing illegal securities offerings. There a=
re various reasons why a crypto project might not have gotten in trouble wi=
th the SEC:
=09Some of them did not do securities offerings. Bitcoin, most notably, nev=
er raised money from investors by selling Bitcoins to build its network; th=
is whole analysis does not apply to Bitcoin, and everyone agrees that it is=
 not a security.=09Some of them did securities offerings, but by the time t=
he SEC noticed they were too entrenched and decentralized and it would have=
 been a pain for the SEC to go after them. Ethereum, most notably,=C2=A0ver=
y very clearly did an ICO in 2014,=C2=A0raising about $18.3 million by sell=
ing ETH tokens. If they did that today, or in late 2017, the SEC would have=
 some serious questions. But by the time the SEC got around to cracking dow=
n on ICOs in 2017, Ethereum was big and decentralized and the SEC would hav=
e had a hard time, practically and legally, challenging its 2014 ICO. And s=
o everyone sort of grudgingly concedes that ETH is not a security.=09Some o=
f them did securities offerings=C2=A0after=C2=A0the SEC started cracking do=
wn, and they learned the right lessons and=C2=A0followed enough best practi=
ces (lockups, SAFTs, not selling in the US, etc.) that the SEC had no real =
cause for complaint. They did=C2=A0legal=C2=A0(private) securities offering=
s.
  [3]

=09Some of them did illegal securities offerings, before or after the SEC g=
ot around to cracking down on ICOs, but the SEC has limited time and attent=
ion and=C2=A0chose not to go after them, because it could get better bang f=
or its enforcement buck by going after different offerings.=09Just wait! Th=
e fact that the SEC has not=C2=A0yet=C2=A0sued any particular crypto projec=
t doesn=E2=80=99t mean that it=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t.=C2=A0

And so the result is that Coinmarketcap.com lists something like 10,408 cry=
pto tokens, and only a handful of them have been sued by the SEC for doing =
illegal securities offerings. The first token on the list is Bitcoin, which=
 the SEC has not sued for Reason 1 above. The second is Ethereum, Reason 2.=
 The third is Tether, which the SEC has not sued for =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, I=
 don=E2=80=99t know, I=E2=80=99m going to go with Reason 5, though I am not=
 sure about that.
  [4]
=C2=A0The fourth is Binance=E2=80=99s BNB token, which the SEC just sued th=
is Monday. Sixth is Ripple=E2=80=99s XRP, which the SEC has been suing sinc=
e 2020.
The more interesting ones, though, are Cardano=E2=80=99s ADA token (No. 7 o=
n the list), Solana=E2=80=99s SOL token (No. 9) and Polygon=E2=80=99s MATIC=
 token (No. 10). The SEC absolutely thinks these tokens are all securities;=
 it said so, in some detail,=C2=A0in  court  filings this week. But it has =
not sued Cardano or Solana or Polygon for selling these tokens illegally. I=
 don=E2=80=99t really know why, but any combination of Reason=C2=A02 (they =
are pretty big and entrenched and decentralized, so it=E2=80=99s hard to ev=
en know who to sue), Reason 3 (they=C2=A0did=C2=A0follow best practices; So=
lana, for instance, sold its tokens through a SAFT and filed forms with the=
 SEC about the offering),=C2=A0Reason 4 (so many tokens, so little time) an=
d Reason 5 (it is still early days) is possible. I would probably bet mostl=
y on Reason 3: These are tokens that were issued in securities offerings to=
 raise money for crypto projects, but they weren=E2=80=99t issued in=C2=A0i=
llegal=C2=A0securities offerings. These projects had good lawyers and were =
launched in a time of sunny optimism for crypto regulation in the US; they =
tried to follow the law as they understood it, and more or less succeeded.
In the last few months or so, the SEC has launched a new and more aggressiv=
e crackdown on crypto than the 2017 version. And its approach is different.
There are two main securities laws in the US, the =E2=80=9933 Act and the =
=E2=80=9934 Act. The =E2=80=9933 Act =E2=80=94=C2=A0the Securities Act of 1=
933 =E2=80=94=C2=A0regulates the issuance=C2=A0of securities: If you want t=
o raise money for your business by selling stocks or bonds, you have to reg=
ister your sales with the Securities and Exchange Commission and give buyer=
s a prospectus with disclosure about your business. The=C2=A0=E2=80=9934 Ac=
t =E2=80=94=C2=A0the Securities Exchange Act of 1934 =E2=80=94=C2=A0regulat=
es the=C2=A0trading=C2=A0of securities: It has rules for stock exchanges an=
d brokers, rules against fraud in stock trading, rules for continuing discl=
osure by companies with publicly traded stock.
The SEC=E2=80=99s 2017ish ICO crackdown was very much a =E2=80=9933 Act cra=
ckdown: People were raising money by selling scammy stock-like tokens, and =
the SEC shut down their scams, one at a=C2=A0time.=C2=A0
And one result of this approach is that Coinmarketcap.com lists 10,408 cryp=
to tokens, and only a handful of them have been sued by the SEC for doing i=
llegal securities offerings. Maybe that=E2=80=99s fine! Maybe the SEC=E2=80=
=99s crackdown on ICOs deterred 30,000 other, scammier crypto projects from=
 launching; maybe the 10,000 current crypto tokens are all pretty good and =
not scammy.
But one could imagine that the SEC disagrees. One could imagine that the SE=
C looks at the 10,000 existing crypto tokens and thinks:
=09Ehhh, a lot of these are scams.=09Scam or not, virtually none of them pr=
ovide the sort of financial and business disclosure that a US public compan=
y would disclose to its shareholders.=09Lots of them trade pretty freely on=
 crypto exchanges, and US retail investors can buy=C2=A0them.

What can the SEC do about it? Well, it can go sue thousands of crypto proje=
cts, but that is hard not only because there are thousands of them but beca=
use many will be decentralized and/or foreign enough that they are hard to =
sue.
Also some of them=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t do anything wrong: Solana, let=E2=80=
=99s say,=C2=A0did=C2=A0do a securities offering of SOL tokens, but=C2=A0le=
gally, selling them to venture capitalists in private placements subject to=
 appropriate SAFTs and lockups. The fact that those tokens=C2=A0now=C2=A0tr=
ade publicly, with less disclosure and fewer investor safeguards than the S=
EC would like, is, from the SEC=E2=80=99s perspective, unfortunate. But it=
=E2=80=99s not exactly Solana=E2=80=99s fault, or rather it is Solana=E2=80=
=99s fault but in a perfectly legal way.
But what the SEC=C2=A0can=C2=A0do is sue crypto=C2=A0exchanges. What it=C2=
=A0can=C2=A0do is try to  shut down Coinbase Inc., the biggest US crypto ex=
change, and  shut Binance, the biggest global crypto exchange, out of the U=
S market. And it can go after other companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0Bittrex, Krake=
n, Gemini =E2=80=94=C2=A0that offer crypto trading to US customers. Because=
 if it is illegal to operate a crypto=C2=A0exchange=C2=A0in the US, then US=
 customers won=E2=80=99t be able to trade crypto, which means that they wil=
l be protected from the bad aspects =E2=80=94=C2=A0the scams, the lack of d=
isclosure, the lack of investor protections =E2=80=94=C2=A0of crypto.
Two quick asides here:
=09Obviously you can disagree with the SEC=E2=80=99s goal here! Just, you k=
now, there is a dial, and one extreme is =E2=80=9CLOTS OF ACCESS TO WORLD-C=
HANGING INNOVATION / ALSO LOTS OF SCAMS,=E2=80=9D and the other extreme is =
=E2=80=9CNO SCAMS / ALSO NO CRYPTO INNOVATION,=E2=80=9D and the SEC clearly=
 wants to jam the dial all the way to the no-scams end, and lots of people =
in crypto, and in Congress, and even in the SEC disagree. =E2=80=9CWe need =
to regulate crypto to prevent scams while also fostering the innovative fin=
ancial products of the future=E2=80=9D is I suppose a plausible thing to th=
ink about crypto; it is just so clearly not what the SEC=E2=80=99s current =
leadership thinks. (Plausibly the SEC comes to this view honestly, by looki=
ng at the actual mix of scams and innovation in crypto so far.)=09Crypto pe=
ople are going to email me to say =E2=80=9Cwell actually you can trade cryp=
to on decentralized exchanges, and even if the SEC shuts down Coinbase and =
Binance, it will never be able to shut down Uniswap, because that is just i=
mmutable code running on the blockchain.=E2=80=9D One: sure, fine. Two: yes=
, but using decentralized exchanges is generally=C2=A0harder=C2=A0than usin=
g Coinbase, and so shutting down centralized exchanges probably=C2=A0would=
=C2=A0serve the SEC=E2=80=99s goal of protecting unsophisticated retail inv=
estors from crypto scams. Three: I highly doubt that=C2=A0the SEC=C2=A0thin=
ks that decentralization is a complete defense from lawsuits, and I=E2=80=
=99d expect to see more cases against DEXes if the current crackdown goes w=
ell for the SEC.

When the SEC sues crypto exchanges, it does so under the =E2=80=9934 Act: T=
he essential argument is not =E2=80=9Cyou are illegally selling securities =
to raise money,=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9Cyou are operating a trading ve=
nue for securities without registering as a securities exchange.=E2=80=9D
  [5]
=C2=A0If the SEC is right about this, then the exchanges need to either shu=
t down, or register with the SEC as securities exchanges (which seems=C2=A0=
very=C2=A0hard to do, given current crypto market structure and the SEC=E2=
=80=99s skepticism about crypto exchanges
  [6]
), or stop listing tokens that are securities (which limits them to, what, =
Bitcoin? Dogecoin? Maybe Ethereum?).=C2=A0
But this gives the exchanges an interesting argument. Their argument takes =
the form:
=09Okay, fine, when crypto projects sell tokens to raise money from investo=
rs to build their project, that=E2=80=99s a securities offering.=09But the=
=C2=A0tokens themselves=C2=A0are not securities forever. Once the project i=
s built and running, the tokens are something else. They are utility tokens=
, currencies, commodities, air miles, Starbucks gift cards, whatever, not s=
ecurities.=09We only trade those tokens.

That is, Solana might have done a=C2=A0securities offering=C2=A0of SOL, but=
 that doesn=E2=80=99t make SOL a security now.
And so when the SEC was threatening to sue Coinbase earlier this year, Coin=
base=E2=80=99s lawyers sent the SEC a Wells submission =E2=80=94=C2=A0basic=
ally, an argument for why it shouldn=E2=80=99t sue Coinbase =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
laying out this argument.
  [7]


As a threshold matter, digital assets are computer code that operate on blo=
ckchain technology. They do not necessarily memorialize any contractual rel=
ationship with an issuer or other party, or=C2=A0inherently constitute secu=
rities. Courts have consistently found that the =E2=80=9Cobject=E2=80=9D of=
 an investment contract is distinguishable from the investment contract=E2=
=80=94each digital asset =E2=80=9Call by itself is not a security, just as =
the orange groves in Howey were not.=E2=80=9D See, e.g., SEC v. ETS Payphon=
es, Inc., 408 F.3d 727, 732=E2=80=9333 (11th Cir. 2005) (scheme involving s=
ale-leaseback of payphones was an investment contract, without suggesting t=
hat the payphones were securities); Kemmerer v. Weaver, 445 F.2d 76, 79=E2=
=80=9380 (7th Cir. 1971) (sales of =E2=80=9Clive breeding beavers=E2=80=9D =
plus service agreements for their care was an investment contract, without =
suggesting that the beavers themselves were securities). Thus, digital asse=
ts implicate the securities laws only when sold as part of an ongoing =E2=
=80=9Cinvestment contract, transaction or scheme.=E2=80=9D ...
Unlike for traditional securities like stocks which represent ongoing claim=
s against an issuer, for the Commission to prevail, it will need to show th=
at particular digital assets are sold as part of investment contracts when =
traded on Coinbase, even though none of the asset issuers, their affiliates=
, or underwriters are in ongoing contractual privity with the purchasers of=
