I don=E2=80=99t really believe this argument. To me, tokens are stock. The =
investment contract involved when a crypto project raises money by selling =
tokens is: =E2=80=9CYou give us money, we will use the money to build a pro=
ject, and you will get tokens that entitle you to some form of economic own=
ership of the project.=E2=80=9D
  [8]
=C2=A0The form of economic ownership is not exactly the=C2=A0same=C2=A0as i=
t is in the case of stock, but it is closely analogous. If you buy a token =
and the project becomes popular, the token will be worth more. The token mi=
ght pay dividends (in the form of staking rewards), or its price might be p=
ropped up by buybacks (burning) paid for out of the revenues of the project=
, just as in the case of corporate stock. It might have some sort of voting=
 or governance rights, or a right to validate transactions in the project. =
But in any case it will go up and down with the popularity of the project, =
of the business; it will remain a speculative investment in the project.
It is all pretty close to being stock, which is why it is a good fundraisin=
g tool. You could imagine a crypto project selling tokens that are=C2=A0not=
=C2=A0meant to go up in value as the project succeeds =E2=80=94=C2=A0tokens=
 that, like airline miles or Starbucks gift cards, are just redeemable for =
a fairly fixed amount of actual product =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that is mostly n=
ot how these projects work. They raise money by selling tokens that are mea=
nt to trade like stock, and the people buying the tokens understand that pr=
oposition. Venture capitalists do not buy airline miles because airline mil=
es do not offer 100x returns. They buy Solana.
Lots of companies sell stock in securities offerings, and then that stock i=
s listed on stock exchanges, and then the companies stop selling stock. Met=
a Platforms Inc. has tons of money and hasn=E2=80=99t sold stock to raise c=
ash since 2013. Does this mean that its stock is not a security, because Me=
ta does =E2=80=9Cnot raise capital from users trading on=E2=80=9D Nasdaq? D=
oes it mean that =E2=80=9Csecondary market transactions=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0trading of Meta stock on Nasdaq =E2=80=94=C2=A0are somehow not transa=
ctions in=C2=A0stock, because Meta is no longer selling stock to raise mone=
y?=C2=A0
I think the better analysis here is =E2=80=9Cthese crypto tokens are a sort=
 of investment contract that looks like stock, and if they are securities w=
