       =20
  [1] That is very much not legal advice and there are many nuances here, b=
ut that is kind of the rough summary of Rule 144.


  [2] In the previous paragraph I say that the SAFT might deliver tokens =
=E2=80=9Cin, say, a year,=E2=80=9D but a SAFT could instead deliver tokens =
upon reaching some milestone of utility: If the project=E2=80=99s blockchai=
n is live and people are using the tokens to, like, store files or pay for =
WiFi or whatever, then the tokens are arguably =E2=80=9Cutility tokens=E2=
=80=9D and not =E2=80=9Csecurities,=E2=80=9D and so it=E2=80=99s no problem=
 for the SAFT to convert into freely tradable tokens, even if it=E2=80=99s =
only been three months since the private placement. Also I should say that =
it=E2=80=99s not clear that the SEC has ever bought into the SAFT idea; in =
2019 it   brought a case against Telegram for selling tokens illegally, arg=
uing that its SAFT didn=E2=80=99t work because the SAFT flipped into tokens=
 before the blockchain ecosystem was *really* functional, and because a *fr=
ee* distribution of tokens to users was itself an illegal securities offeri=
ng.


  [3] There is essentially no meaningful category of =E2=80=9Cthey sold tok=
ens to the public in registered offerings following SEC rules,=E2=80=9D tho=
ugh there are occasional minor examples. The crypto projects that did legal=
 securities offerings overwhelmingly did legal *private* (or offshore) offe=
rings.


  [4] Okay *I* actually think that non-interest-bearing stablecoins are *no=
t securities*, Reason 1, but I think the SEC disagrees. Its Binance complai=
nt on Monday alleges that Binance=E2=80=99s BUSD stablecoin is a security. =
See paragraphs 315 to 324 of the complaint, arguing that =E2=80=9CBinance h=
as, from the outset, marketed BUSD=E2=80=99s profit-earning potential and r=
eferred to the various =E2=80=98APYs=E2=80=99 (annual percentage yield) tha=
t investors may earn with respect to their BUSD holdings.=E2=80=9D I think =
that that at most means the lending programs are securities, not that BUSD =
itself is. But the SEC thinks otherwise. More generally, a stablecoin is pl=
ausibly equivalent to a money market mutual fund, which *is* a security. Al=
so separately Tether seems to live its life in such a way as to maximize it=
s chances of getting in trouble with US regulators, so it would be a little=
 stunning if the SEC *never* gets around to suing it.


  [5] [5] This oversimplifies, and in fact the SEC does sue exchanges for =
=E2=80=9933 Act violations: for offering their own tokens (in the case of B=
inance=E2=80=99s BNB token), or for offering lending and staking programs t=
hat the SEC argues are securities. (The SEC=E2=80=99s Gemini and Kraken cas=
es are entirely about this.) But it is *relatively* easy to strip away thos=
e offerings and just run an exchange that offers crypto trading with no exc=
hange token, no staking-as-a-service and no lending program. To really shut=
 down trading the SEC has to bring =E2=80=9934 Act charges alleging that th=
e core business of the exchange is itself illegal, and that is what it did =
with Bittrex, Binance and Coinbase.


  [6] The big issues here would include splitting the functions of exchange=
, broker-dealer and clearinghouse: In normal securities exchanges those are=
 separate independent entities, but in crypto they are ordinarily combined.=
 But the SEC would find lots of other problems. Code of conduct for exchang=
e members! Listing standards for tokens! Periodic corporate disclosure for =
tokens! Here is a paper from the Committee on Capital Markets Regulation ti=
tled =E2=80=9CCryptoasset Trading Platforms Cannot Register as Securities E=
xchanges"; you get the idea. The SEC will tell crypto exchanges =E2=80=9Cco=
me in and register,=E2=80=9D but I think that is best analyzed as a dark jo=
ke, and the enforcement actions are meant to shut down crypto exchanges, no=
t to force them to register.


  [7] The submission discusses the =E2=80=9CHowey test=E2=80=9D for whether=
 something is an =E2=80=9Cinvestment contract,=E2=80=9D which we  discussed=
 yesterday; basically if a thing is an investment contract =E2=80=94 =E2=80=
=9Can investment of money in a common enterprise with profits to come solel=
y from the efforts of others=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 then it qualifies as a secu=
rity. This test comes from a 1946 Supreme Court case about a promoter who s=
old investors orange groves plus a management contract: The promoter would =
grow, harvest and sell your oranges for you, and send you the profits. Was =
this a real estate deal, or a securities offering? Securities, said the Sup=
reme Court: The grove plus management constituted an investment contract.


  [8] This is different from the oranges in Howey, or the beavers in Kemmer=
er. If you bought those investment contracts you got oranges, or beavers (?=
), which are categories of things that exist in the world independent of th=
e efforts of an investment promoter. If you buy SOL you get SOL, a bit of c=
omputer code, which is worth $0 if the promoters of Solana do not build and=
 promote a popular blockchain and a lot of money if they do.


