10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">SEC v. crypto exchanges</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The US Securities and Exchange Commission <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31722938.259418/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTctMTItMDUvc2VjLWhhb=
HRzLWEtc2lsbHktaW5pdGlhbC1jb2luLW9mZmVyaW5nP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MDcyM19NT05FWVNU=
VUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDY=
wNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB31d84916" item=
prop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #cc=
c;">began cracking down on crypto in 2017</a>. At the time, there was a vog=
ue for what were called ICOs, initial coin offerings, in which some crypto =
company or project=C2=A0would raise money by selling crypto tokens to publi=
c investors. The ICO promoters =E2=80=94=C2=A0the people behind the crypto =
project =E2=80=94=C2=A0would put out a white paper describing their project=
 and promising brilliant innovations and huge profits, and they would=C2=A0=
sell a bunch of tokens for money. There would generally be very little in t=
he way of disclosure or investor rights. For promoters, the ICO was attract=
ive because it was a way to raise a lot of money from enthusiastic and gull=
ible retail investors without following securities laws. Many, many, many I=
COs turned out to be <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/31722938.259418/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJpdGNvaW4uY29tLzQ2LWxhc3QteWVhcnMtaWNv=
cy1mYWlsZWQtYWxyZWFkeS8/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1fd299a4" itemprop=3D"Stor=
yLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">complete=
 vaporware</a>, either frauds or functionally indistinguishable from frauds=
.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For the SEC, the ICO was obviously illegal: Th=
ese tokens were obviously securities, and the ICOs were obviously unregiste=
red securities offerings. (Also, many of them were frauds.)=C2=A0And so the=
 SEC started bringing enforcement actions against ICO promoters, basically =
making them give the money back and promise not to do it again, and the ICO=
 boom quickly fizzled.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC, I think, learned three lessons from t=
his experience:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Almost all crypto tokens are securiti=
es.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Winning (or settling) cases ag=
ainst crypto projects for doing illegal securities offerings is pretty easy=
.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Especially when they are also fr=
auds.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The crypto industry also learned some lessons =
from this experience. The =E2=80=9CICO,=E2=80=9D as an initialism, went awa=
y, but crypto projects kept selling tokens to raise money. But a new set of=
 best practices emerged that more or less conceded the SEC=E2=80=99s point =
that selling tokens to raise money to build a project is a securities offer=
ing. Startup crypto projects largely stopped selling tokens to public retai=
l investors in the US: They might sell to retail investors in more crypto-f=
riendly jurisdictions, but in the US they would only sell to accredited ins=
titutional investors, crypto hedge funds and venture capitalists. (Under US=
 securities laws, private offerings to institutional investors are exempt f=
rom registration requirements.) The venture capitalists would sign a lockup=
, agreeing not to sell their tokens for some period of time. (Under US secu=
rities laws, selling securities to a venture capitalist who immediately tur=
ns around to dump them on the public is treated as a public securities offe=
ring, but if the VC holds the securities for at least a year, she can sell =
them freely.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color=
: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bord=
er-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-=
color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The project might=C2=A0do what is called a SAF=
T, a =E2=80=9Csimple agreement for future tokens,=E2=80=9D in which the VC =
pays the crypto project now and gets back a contract promising delivery of =
the project=E2=80=99s tokens in, say, a year. The theory here is that the S=
AFT fundraising is a securities offering =E2=80=94=C2=A0the crypto project =
is selling investment contracts for cash =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the underlying=
=C2=A0<em>tokens=C2=A0</em>are not securities; the=C2=A0<em>tokens </em>are=
 just a form of currency for use in the crypto project. They are, in crypto=
 lingo, =E2=80=9Cutility tokens=E2=80=9D; people buy them not as speculativ=
e investments in a business but to=C2=A0<em>use=C2=A0</em>them to do crypto=
-y stuff.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have sometimes <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/31722938.259418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMTAtMTQvdGhlLXNlYy1yZWFsbHktZG9lc24tdC1saW=
tlLWljb3M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYwNzIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc=
291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNjA3JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBdd876e6e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">explained ICOs</a> by saying th=
at =E2=80=9Cthey=E2=80=99re like if the Wright Brothers sold air miles to f=
inance inventing the airplane.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Raising financing from investo=
rs to build a speculative new technology=C2=A0<em>feels like a securities o=
ffering</em>, so ICOs are securities offerings, but=C2=A0<em>actually exist=
ing airline miles=C2=A0</em>are not securities: They are a loyalty program,=
 a way to pay for an airline seat. The SAFT concept is a way to embody this=
 difference: Selling the tokens before the project exists is a securities=
=C2=A0offering, but once the project is running and the tokens are useful, =
the tokens are just tokens, not securities. And so the SAFT might say that =
the VC pays now to get tokens in the future, and the SAFT actually delivers=
 the tokens when the project is up and running and the tokens are useful.<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SAFT is not the only way to do it, though;=
 even if the tokens are always securities, selling them in private placemen=
ts to VCs and locking the VCs up for a year is more or less a way to comply=
 with securities laws. Broadly speaking, the US securities laws regulate mo=
stly=C2=A0<em>public=C2=A0</em>sales of securities, widespread sales to ret=
ail investors; private placements to big investors are less regulated.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In any case there are plenty of crypto project=
s, these days, that the SEC has=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>gone after for doing=
 illegal securities offerings. There are various reasons why a crypto proje=
ct might not have gotten in trouble with the SEC:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Some of them did not do securities of=
ferings. Bitcoin, most notably, never raised money from investors by sellin=
g Bitcoins to build its network; this whole analysis does not apply to Bitc=
oin, and everyone agrees that it is not a security.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">Some of them did securities offerings, but by the time th=
e SEC noticed they were too entrenched and decentralized and it would have =
been a pain for the SEC to go after them. Ethereum, most notably,=C2=A0<em>=
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31722938.259418/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9mZWF0dXJlcy8yMDIyLXRoZS1jcnlwdG8tc3RvcnkvP=
2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MDcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1u=
ZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDYwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZiNhLWRpc3R=
yaWJ1dGVkLWNvbXB1dGVy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0d3eb075" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">very very =
