=A0inherently constitute securities. Courts have consistently found that th=
e =E2=80=9Cobject=E2=80=9D of an investment contract is distinguishable fro=
m the investment contract=E2=80=94each digital asset =E2=80=9Call by itself=
 is not a security, just as the orange groves in Howey were not.=E2=80=9D <=
em>See, e.g., SEC </em>v.<em> ETS Payphones, Inc.</em>, 408 F.3d 727, 732=
=E2=80=9333 (11th Cir. 2005) (scheme involving sale-leaseback of payphones =
was an investment contract, without suggesting that the payphones were secu=
rities); <em>Kemmerer</em> v. <em>Weaver</em>, 445 F.2d 76, 79=E2=80=9380 (=
7th Cir. 1971) (sales of =E2=80=9Clive breeding beavers=E2=80=9D plus servi=
ce agreements for their care was an investment contract, without suggesting=
 that the beavers themselves were securities). Thus, digital assets implica=
te the securities laws only when sold as part of an ongoing =E2=80=9Cinvest=
ment contract, transaction or scheme.=E2=80=9D ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Unlike for traditional securities like stocks =
which represent ongoing claims against an issuer, for the Commission to pre=
vail, it will need to show that particular digital assets are sold as part =
of investment contracts when traded on Coinbase, even though none of the as=
set issuers, their affiliates, or underwriters are in ongoing contractual p=
rivity with the purchasers of those digital assets. ... In its recent <em>B=
ittrex</em> complaint, the Commission alleged in a conclusory manner that c=
ertain assets were continually =E2=80=9Coffered=E2=80=9D as an investment c=
ontract, years after their initial offerings, even where management of the =
associated protocol had changed or was distributed to users.=C2=A0But no co=
urt would allow the Commission to assume these are =E2=80=9Congoing=E2=80=
=9D investment schemes without proving as much on an individualized basis.=
=C2=A0...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Prior cases applying <em>Howey</em> to digital=
 assets have overwhelmingly targeted digital asset issuers, not exchanges. =
In these cases, the Commission has charged the issuer or promoter of a digi=
tal asset with raising capital from investors in exchange for digital asset=
s, whose value would be based on the success of the issuer or promoter=E2=
=80=99s business. ... It was argued that the issuer entered into an =E2=80=
=9Cimplicit=E2=80=9D contract with the initial buyer, at a specific point i=
n time, to develop the business in exchange for funding. =E2=80=A6 No such =
legal theory will be available in a case against Coinbase because, again, n=
o issuer can raise capital from users trading on Coinbase.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, even if each asset issuer were engaged=
 in ongoing marketing efforts at the time of each transaction on Coinbase, =
and even if those ongoing marketing efforts were somehow viewed as sufficie=
nt to establish an implicit investment contract (e.g., as a scheme), it doe=
s not follow that secondary market transactions implicate that investment c=
ontract.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t really believe this argument. =
To me, tokens are <em>stock</em>. The investment contract involved when a c=
rypto project raises money by selling tokens is: =E2=80=9CYou give us money=
, we will use the money to build a project, and you will get tokens that en=
title you to some form of economic ownership of the project.=E2=80=9D<a cla=
ss=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-8" style=3D"color: #000000; text-de=
coration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #=
000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent=
 !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[8]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The form of economic ownership is not exactly the=C2=A0<em>same=
=C2=A0</em>as it is in the case of stock, but it is closely analogous. If y=
ou buy a token and the project becomes popular, the token will be worth mor=
e. The token might pay dividends (in the form of staking rewards), or its p=
rice might be propped up by buybacks (burning) paid for out of the revenues=
 of the project, just as in the case of corporate stock. It might have some=
 sort of voting or governance rights, or a right to validate transactions i=
n the project. But in any case it will go up and down with the popularity o=
f the project, of the business; it will remain a speculative investment in =
the project.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It is all pretty close to being stock, which i=
s why it is a good fundraising tool. You could imagine a crypto project sel=
ling tokens that are=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>meant to go up in value as the =
project succeeds =E2=80=94=C2=A0tokens that, like airline miles or Starbuck=
s gift cards, are just redeemable for a fairly fixed amount of actual produ=
ct =E2=80=94=C2=A0but that is mostly not how these projects work. They rais=
e money by selling tokens that are meant to trade like stock, and the peopl=
e buying the tokens understand that proposition. Venture capitalists do not=
 buy airline miles because airline miles do not offer 100x returns. They bu=
y Solana.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Lots of companies sell stock in securities off=
erings, and then that stock is listed on stock exchanges, and then the comp=
anies stop selling stock. Meta Platforms Inc. has tons of money and hasn=E2=
=80=99t sold stock to raise cash since 2013. Does this mean that its stock =
is not a security, because Meta does =E2=80=9Cnot raise capital from users =
trading on=E2=80=9D Nasdaq? Does it mean that =E2=80=9Csecondary market tra=
nsactions=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0trading of Meta stock on Nasdaq =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0are somehow not transactions in=C2=A0stock, because Meta is no longer=
 selling stock to raise money?=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think the better analysis here is =E2=80=9Ct=
hese crypto tokens are a sort of investment contract that looks like stock,=
 and if they are securities when they are offered then they are securities =
forever, and if you run an exchange that lists these securities then it is =
a securities exchange.=E2=80=9D And if that analysis=C2=A0is=C2=A0wrong and=
 Coinbase is right, then it means that crypto has essentially discovered a =
way to sell unregulated stock: You can include most of the economic feature=
s of stock in a crypto token, and if you sell it to venture capitalists and=
 wait a year then you never have to worry about securities regulation.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But this is a real argument! It is obviously p=
opular in crypto circles, but it also has some fans in Congress. Bloomberg'=
s Allyson Versprille <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/31722938.259418/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MjMtMDYtMDIva2V5LWhvdXNlLXJlcHVibGljYW5zLXVudmVpbC1jcnlwdG8tbWFya2V0LXN0cnV=
jdHVyZS1kcmFmdC1iaWxsP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA2MDcyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW=
1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDYwNyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249b=
W9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCce9438ee" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  reported last we=
ek</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Republican chairs of two key House committees =
released a draft bill that would offer a pathway for digital assets that be=
gin as securities to eventually be regulated as commodities.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The draft legislation was unveiled Friday by H=
ouse Financial Services Committee Chairman Patrick McHenry and House Agricu=
lture Committee Chairman Glenn Thompson. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The 162-page draft bill will likely face long =
odds getting the agreement from Democrats in Congress needed for it to beco=
me law but it offers a glimpse into Republicans=E2=80=99 thinking on the is=
sue after months of calling for a regulatory framework for digital assets.=
=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Tokens offered as part of an investment contra=
ct would remain in the Securities and Exchange Commission=E2=80=99s remit, =
while those that qualify as commodities would be overseen by the Commodity =
Futures Trading Commission. Whether or not an asset is a commodity would de=
pend largely on whether a blockchain network is decentralized.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You know: Someone wants to start a crypto proj=
ect, they sell tokens of that project to raise money to build it, they buil=
d it, the project becomes an open decentralized blockchain ecosystem that i=
s no longer controlled by the people who built it. When they sell the token=
s to build the project, the tokens are securities; when the project is buil=
t and decentralized, the tokens are commodities. It is a plausible path for=
 crypto regulation. I do not think that it is=C2=A0<em>currently the law=C2=
=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s why they have to propose legislation!=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0but others disagree.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway the basic point here is that the SEC ha=
s mostly had a pretty easy time arguing that crypto tokens are securities, =
when it has sued crypto projects for issuing crypto tokens to raise money. =
(Though it=E2=80=99s still mired in a fight with Ripple.) =E2=80=9CThis guy=
=C2=A0raised money for his business by selling speculative tokens to retail=
 investors=E2=80=9D just looks=C2=A0<em>so=C2=A0</em>much like a securities=
 offering that the SEC is usually going to win that case, especially if it =
can add =E2=80=9Calso the business was a scam.=E2=80=9D It is sensible and =
understandable and, I think, basically correct to extend that reasoning to =
say =E2=80=9Cand if all these crypto projects were raising money by selling=
 securities, then surely an exchange where those securities trade is a secu=
rities exchange.=E2=80=9D But it is not=C2=A0<em>quite </em>that simple.</p=
